It’s race week!  @runcim262 is on Sunday!  Kind of crazy.  Also exciting!  I have to say that when I set the goal for myself this year to run the Olympic Trials qualifying time in the marathon (under 2:37, which is a 5:59/mile pace), I didn’t really expect that it would be that hard for me to do.  But what I’ve learned over the past year is that when you de-prioritize your athletic goals and put family and establishing yourself in a new career first, achieving your goals gets harder and more complicated.  I remember when I went from working full time to racing professionally how much better I started training and performing, because I was doing all the small stuff.  And I’ve had the reverse experience now, going from racing full time to fitting it in to my busy life. Even with all this prep I still don’t feel like I am running as well or feeling as strong as I used to. I laughed with a friend recently as I explained that as a pro athlete it is your JOB to fit everything in- the training, the recovery, the nutrition, the strength , the body work.  Now, I just do what I can, and often that has meant running 1x per day, doing 10’ strength sessions on the fly, not giving much thought to nutrition and managing on 6 or less hours of sleep.  It has given me SO MUCH MORE respect for all the parents out there who work full time, make time for their families and still train.  You are all serious rock stars 🌟 
.
.
I’m really proud of myself and what I did accomplish during this build, and I am ready to lay it out there on Sunday and go for the OTQ! The one thing I always do is believe in what I can accomplish go for it with reckless abandon.  No regrets!  Let’s see what happens on Sunday!
.
Huge shout out to my team @riseathleticsboulder, my coach @ricrojasrunningtrack and all my training buddies who were part of getting to this start line. 🙌😍😍
.
.
#lovetorun #matathon #marathonotq #olympictrials #running #polarusa #clifbar #letsdothis

CIM 2022!  I’m about 2.5 weeks late on this post but here we go!
.
.
The qualifying standard for the Olympic Trials is 2:37 or faster (under 5:59/mile) and I went into this race feeling like I could do it, but also maybe not.  I felt like it was at the top end of where my fitness was but I wanted to go for it and see!  I’m all about trying and failing vs not trying at all. 
.
.
It is funny because I was reading @bethgmckenzie’s post about her race, all her emotions around it mirrored mine!  The first 20 miles I kept thinking “this feels so easy!  I’ve got this in the bag!  I went through 13.1 miles in 1:17+ and was about 1.5 minutes under pace at mile 20. But then I hit mile 21 and that was the end of me 🤣. I suffered my way through the last 5 miles and crossed the line in 2:41 - 4 full minutes off the time I needed to run 🤦‍♀️. Talk about blow up 🤪. Part was probably fitness, part nutrition, part pacing - lots to work on for the next one 😍
.
.
Of course I’m disappointed and there is a fire to do another marathon and reach my goal.  But at the end of the day - maybe because I’m older, or because my priorities have changed, or because I just can’t commit myself in the way I have in the past - I felt happy and content.  I did what I could to prepare.  I had a BLAST being out there racing, and I loved the process of getting to the start line and training with my @riseathleticsboulder team (👊 to my bud @kwatsrun). I could have felt devastated to not meet my goal, but my feelings were more of gratitude for the opportunity. I felt proud to have achieved what I did with where I am at this year in my life. 
.
.
A HUGE shout out to @wynrepublic @malorepublic for my amazingly comfy and high-performing kit (side note: Beth and I started racing triathlon together WAY back in the day so it felt extra special to be racing together and for me to be wearing her beautifully designed clothes). And a special shout out to @clifbar @polarusa @rideshimano @ixcelaperformance @bearmattress @andmother_org - I am coming to the end of relationships that spanned all or the majority of my career as an athlete and I am SO honored to have been able to represent these brands. 
.
.
✌️

Diving in to another year in Real Estate and I’m SO PUMPED to kick off 2023!  I know 2022 felt like a tale of two markets for most, but I’m so optimistic about the opportunities for both buyers and sellers in the market.  As a seller - 2022 still ended the year UP 📈in terms of YoY home price growth (~11% ⬆️ in the Denver Metro area). And while the markets are softer (and evening declining a bit) today, sellers are still locking in the tremendous equity gains from the pandemic home price growth. That is a WIN!
.
.
As a buyer - this market provides such an awesome opportunity!  Buyers are in the driver’s seat!  With the chance to get a home at below list price, have inspection repairs covered for you, AND have sellers pay to buy down your interest rate ….the opportunities to negotiate a fantastic deal are endless. 
.
.
Think about it - would you rather pay $50k-$150k over asking, and then have $5,000-$20,000 (or more) of repairs but have a low interest rate??…… OR would you rather pay a higher interest rate today that you can refinance in a year or two, but get a house for $25k under asking, have the sellers do all the repairs for you, AND pay all your closing costs? 🤔.
.
.
To me, this market is a win win.  Sellers can pull out huge amounts of equity, and buyers are finally able to buy the home of their dreams at a reasonable price 💪.
.
.
Thinking about buying or selling in the Boulder/ Denver area?  I’d love to help you out!
.
.
#realestate #sellingcolorado #8zrealestate #boulder #boulderrealestate #2023realestate #letsgo #opportunity 📸: @mtn_techne

Let’s talk CURB APPEAL:  whether you like it or not, curb appeal makes all the difference when selling your home.

There is the “curb appeal trifecta”: mulch, seasonal color, and a pressure-sprayed driveway. 

BUT…if you want to take things a step further, then add these three things to the front of your home to level up your outdoor game:

💡 Illuminate walkways. Would-be buyers are sure to do a nighttime drive-by (trust me, they will). Ambient outdoor lighting will have them oohing and ahhing. (Quick tip: Solar lights make this super easy!)
.
.
✨ Update porch lights. Replace crooked, outdated, or rusty porch lights with something fresh and modern. Your local home improvement store and a couple of hours are all you need.
.
.
🛋️ Add seating with outdoor throw pillows. Everyone dreams of a breezy afternoon in the yard, sipping a cold glass of lemonade. Add seating to give buyers an exact place to do just that.

Having your home look BEAUTIFUL on the outside drives traffic and increases the chances of selling your home quickly!  Want to learn more?  Give me a call!  I’d love to help!
.
.
PS - yes…this is a schematic of what the outside of our home will eventually look like: new siding (weathered cedar), new porch, new garage door, new landscaping and new lighting!  And…we might just add some outdoor seating and throw pillows to the porch!
.
.
.
#8z #anewwayhome #curbappeal #coloradolawns #coloradohomes #coloradoneighborhoods

.
.
When we met, he had tried to sell his home at the peak of the market in 2021 to no avail.  He said that the most important things for him were getting it under contract and sold quickly. The result: we did over 40 showings in 3 days, received 5 total offers, went under contract in 5 days, and closed in 2 weeks at $19,000 over asking.  Im fact, it sold at the price he was asking for it (when it didn’t sell) in 2021. He was THRILLED!

.
The key to getting a home sold quickly: Condition of the home, marketing (including staging), and price.  We nailed all 3 and today - 3 weeks after listing his house, he is on the road to his new home state!

I don’t really believe in balance, more that at any point in time we put more weight on certain aspects of our lives than others.  Over the last 1.5 years there has been a meaningful shift in my life - where sport has shifted from both a passion AND my job to just a passion that understandably has assumed a pretty low place on my priority totem pole of life.  And though this shift is what I want, I still CRAVE movement, the feeling of fitness and also competition.  My priorities right now are my family, my community, and my job.  But it has been hard to me to figure out what place sport and running can still play.  I’ve asked myself so many times - is it ok to want to compete?  Will it take too much time away from family?  Will it take too much time away from other things I want to do?  Is it fulfilling me? I’ve found myself often in this weird place of wanting to commit and get faster and fitter and then wanting to pull back and take a more casual approach.  I go to practice and feel frustrated to not be running better, but then have to remind myself that I’m not doing the work to deserve that.  I’ve hesitated all year to commit to a marathon because I felt like it took up too much of my limited spare time and time away from family. BUT…..that Olympic Trials qualification looms large and it is a goal I can’t give up on….so…I’m throwing myself in…one more time to see if I can get that trials qualifying time.  I’m all signed up for an October marathon and am excited to go all in and give myself a shot.
.
.
Also - if anyone has any tips on how to reach your athletic goals while being a parent, working full time, trying to be a spouse/partner, ideally get more than 6 hours of sleep AND have time for other interests I’d love the tips!
.
.
#marathontraining #letsgo #onemoretime #goingallin #running

My little boy is off to pre-school 🤯. I definitely am having a hard time connecting the fact that he was just toddling around and learning to walk a year ago and now he is going to school ?!?!?!😬😬. He was SO excited this morning - when I got him up the first thing he said was “mama I’m going to school today and I make new friends!” 🥰🥰🥰. My heart.  Harrison never ceases to amaze me with his independence and love of life 💙….what a life moment - sending your first born to school for the first time…
.
.
.
#boymom #preschool #lifemoments #twoandahalf #family #school

Feeling SO proud of Harrison right now.  After his initial excitement to go to school, the next several days were TOUGH.  He was anxious, overwhelmed, feeling a bit lonely and afraid of all the newness he was surrounded by.  After the first day of school, as I was putting him in his car seat, he said “mama, I missed you today.  I watched you walk away out the window and I cried” 😭😭😭. Every day that we dropped him off seemed a bit worse… leaving your kid while they scream for you is one of the worst feelings ever. 
.
.
But then on Wednesday he made a new friend, Jane.  And yesterday when I dropped him off he didn’t cry.  And last night when we asked him what he was excited about for the next day he said “going to school!”. 
.
.
As parents we learn that for your child to grow, they have to be stressed and challenged, even when it is hard to watch them go through the discomfort of adjusting to new challenges.  But…we are getting there, and I already see Harrison maturing.  Today he climbed into his car seat on his own and keeps telling me “I do myself!” After just a week in school.  I’m so so proud of this guy.  He earned his trip to the ice cream shop tonight 🍦 🥰🥰
.
.
.
#parenting101 #growingpains #2yearsold #school #growingup

Time to geek out for a moment!! I’m a HUGE fan of numbers and data and this market and all the ups and downs gets me excited every day to dig into the stats…
.
.
💵 Interest rates are highest they have been in years, why would it make sense to buy right now?? How does renting compare from a cost perspective to owning?  Is it really better to own than rent?

….I was fortunate enough to sit down with Brady Mullen from American Liberty Mortgage 🔔 several weeks ago and we had an awesome conversation about how much renting costs vs owning and just how much owning increases your wealth. 
.
.
In short: renting will be “cheaper” than owning in the short term (from a cash flow perspective - meaning how much money you are outlaying every month), but in the medium term renting becomes more expensive than owning and over the long term is a MUCH more expensive….to the tune of thousands of dollars per month. 
.
.
Take a look at this snippet from our recent conversation, and if you are interested in watching the full convo, clink on the YouTube link in my bio!
.
.

Contemplating a 'For Sale' sign among your December decorations?

Here are a few thoughts to help you minimize stress, stay in the festive spirit, and secure a quick sale 👇 

✅ The Do’s 

⚪ Embrace the season: Decorate tastefully to showcase your home's holiday charm and help buyers envision their own future celebrations in your space.

⚪ Cozy up: Create a warm, inviting atmosphere with soft lighting, comfy throws, and delightful scents.

⚪ Stay flexible: December is a hectic time for everyone. Be accommodating with showing schedules to make the process smoother for all parties involved.

🚫 The Don'ts

⚪ Overdo decor: Less is more when it comes to holiday decorations. Avoid overwhelm and let your home's layout, lighting, and features shine.

⚪ Forget basic upkeep: Amidst the holiday hustle, remember essential home upkeep. A well-maintained home makes a first — and lasting — impression on buyers.

⚪ Over-personalize: Clear out personal items and excess clutter to help buyers visualize living within your four walls.

Remember, December buyers are serious buyers, so do what you can to create a space that they can envision as their own.
.
.
.
#anewwayhome #coloradorealtor #realestatetips #tipsforhomesellers #letschat #8z

Interest rates climbed sharply last year, reaching almost 8% by October. So many people are asking: What’s in store for 2024?

⚪ The December Dip: To everyone’s relief, we saw in mid December that mortgage rates dropped below 7% for the first time since August 2023. This is a good sign heading into 2024.

⚪ Rate Outlook Decreasing: While some experts predict rates will increase in early 2024, most believe they will decrease as the year progresses, possibly falling into the high-5’s to low-6’s by year-end.

⚪ Economic Factors Influence: This trend highly depends on economic factors, including Federal Reserve policies, the relationship between various interest rates, and other economic indicators like unemployment and inflation rates. Definitely something to keep an eye on.

⚪ Staying Informed: The future isn’t set in stone, but staying informed about potential changes can make all the difference. 

Whether you’re buying, selling, or just browsing, I LOVE to talk about market dynamics and influences and am always excited to have a conversation, so feel free to reach out!  I can’t wait to see what is in store for 2024
.
.
.

GREAT agents don’t just help their clients find A house….we help them find the RIGHT house.  The key is listening to their wants and needs, asking lots of questions and digging in to the why behind what they are looking for.  In my buyer consultations I have all my clients each and independently write down their top 8-10 must haves for a house, then beside each write down WHY they want that thing.  And then I have them ⭐️ their top 3-4 items.  This ensures a few things:
.
1. When you dig into the “Why” behind a want you often can uncover a lot of information that often opens up the pool of homes to look at.  Someone wanting a 4 BR house may really want 3 BRs + Office.  Or wanting to live next to a golf course because they really just want the feeling of space.

2. Couples don’t always have the same priorities and wants in a home.  This exercise helps them articulate what is most important to each person so that they can find a home together that meets BOTH of their biggest needs.
.
.
Listening, learning and communication are crucial to helping buyers find a home that is truly the best fit for them, and helping them feel listened to and heard by their agent.  The buying process becomes much more fun for all and clients feel in complete control of and confident in their decisions!
.
.
